About the Datasets

A store has a retail credit card available to customers. There can be a number of sources of loss from this product, but one is customers defaulting on their debt.This prevents the store from collecting payment for products and services rendered.

Examing a slice of the customer database with 150,000 customers, we find that 6.6% of customers were seriously delinquent in payment the last two years.

Thus, if only 5% of their carried debt was the store credit card this is potentially an average loss of 8.12 dollars per customer and a potential overall loss of 1.2 million dollars.

In our dataset, each customer has 10 attributes :

  • the total balance on credit cards and personal lines of credit except real estate and no instalment debt such as car loans divided by the sum of credit limits (denoted UnsecuredLines)
  • the age of the borrower (in years)
  • the number of times a borrower has been between 30 and 59 days past due but not worse in the last 2 years (denoted UnderSixtyDaysPast)
  • the monthly debt payments, alimony and living costs over the monthly gross income (denoted DebtRatio)
  • the monthly income (denoted MonthlyIncome)
  • the number of open loeans (like car loan or mortgage) and credit lines (credit cards) (denoted CreditLinesAndLoans)
  • the number of mortgage and real estate loans including home equity lines of credit (denoted RealEstateLoansOrLines)
  • the number of times a borrower has been 90 days or more past due (denoted NinetyDaysLate)
  • the number of times a borrower has been between 60 and 89 days past due but not worse in the last 2 years (denoted UnderNinetyDaysPastDue)
  • the number of dependents in family excluding themselves (spouse, children, etc.) (denoted NumberOfDependents)

To resolve the problematic, we will first develop penalized methods to avoid all multicolinearities risks in our dataset while performing one of the simplest models. Then, we will increase the complexity of our models by introducing Decision Trees and Agregation Methods. The main objective is to compare our results and then decide which model is the best for our dataset.

Global Analysis :

Before starting our study, we would first like to explain the restatements of variables that were necessary prior to the modeling, and also to justify our model choices.

Missing data

Our database contains 10 explanatory variables and one identification variable. We begin our study with an analysis of the missing data in our database.

We see that our database contains a relatively high percentage of missing values, and that deleting them would therefore result in a loss of far too much information. In order to deal with these data, we apply a simple median imputation method, so as not to bias our data. Other, more complex methods would obviously have been possible, but we will always prefer to start with the simplest methods and enrich them if necessary.

Once the problem of missing values is solved, we can divide our database into two subsamples: a train sample composed of 70% of our data and a test sample composed of 30% of our data. In order to ensure a correct learning of our data, we need to make sure that our subsamples are representative, namely that they should each contain about 6.7% of failures.

Outliers

Another problem encountered during our exploratory data analysis is the strong presence of outliers, visible even during the construction of some histograms. The outliers are a problem insofar as they constitute exceptional data or falsely filled data (a negative or zero age in our case for example).

In order to solve the problem of zero age, we decided to declare the modality 0 as missing value, so that it can be reprocessed by an imputation by the median.

Apart from the age variable, we also notice the presence of many exceptional outliers. We decide to reprocess them by applying a Winsorizing method, i.e.by replacing the values higher than the \(\alpha\) quantile by the value of this quantile. We choose a threshold of 5%.

New Variables

Having correctly restated all our variables, we decide to enrich our model by introducing new variables, including variable crossings and new variables.

At first, we can rightly assume that age and income do not have a linear relationship with default. Indeed, a quadratic effect would make more sense for these two variables. We can say that an individual is very risky at a young age, then less risky in the middle of his or her working life, only to become very risky again at retirement age. Similarly, in terms of income, a trade study leads us to believe that the observed effect is not perfectly linear.

In a second step, we can decide to cross-tabulate some of our variables, based on the correlation matrix obtained. In order to facilitate the interpretations, we start by discretizing our variables to be crossed and then, carry out our crossings of variables.

Resampling

As discussed in the presentation of our database, we observe a default rate of about 6.67% in our sample, which is really low and thus may lead to problems of underestimation of the minority class. It is therefore necessary to resample our train sub-sample to satisfy a 50-50 split between our default and non-default classes.
To do this, we apply an algorithm based on a combination of undersampling and oversampling, to ensure that the data we process will not be predominantly synthetic.

Which Metric To Use ?

A final key question remains unresolved and is central to all the models we wish to establish. The metric to use when selecting and validating our models is a key criterion, because if we do not apply the right metric, our conclusions may be completely different.

Our study focuses on a classification problem, namely determining whether a customer has defaulted or not (binary) from a set of explanatory variables forming our dataset.

Several metrics can be considered in our case:

  • the accuracy which indicates the precision of our model and is obtained by the following formula :

\[Accuracy = \frac{Number~Of~Correct~Predictions}{Total~Number~Of~Predictions}\]

  • the ASE which indicates the mean square error and which is obtained by the following formula:

\[ASE = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2}{n}\]

Our objective being a decision, i.e.to classify an individual, we will focus more on the accuracy, and more precisely on the sensitivity, i.e.the number of individuals who have really failed and correctly identified by the models. From the point of view of a default, it seems to be more interesting to identify the individuals who have actually defaulted. We will therefore judge the quality of our models essentially through two tools: the confusion matrix and the AUC or Area Under the Curve.
